member.name: F:Schema.NET.MedicalSpecialty.Podiatric

member.name: P:Schema.NET.MedicalBusiness.Type

member.name: T:Schema.NET.MedicalCause
member.summary: The causative agent(s) that are responsible for the pathophysiologic process that eventually results in a medical condition, symptom or sign. In this schema, unless otherwise specified this is meant to be the proximate cause of the medical condition, symptom or sign. The proximate cause is defined as the causative agent that most directly results in the medical condition, symptom or sign. For example, the HIV virus could be considered a cause of AIDS. Or in a diagnostic context, if a patient fell and sustained a hip fracture and two days later sustained a pulmonary embolism which eventuated in a cardiac arrest, the cause of the cardiac arrest (the proximate cause) would be the pulmonary embolism and not the fall. Medical causes can include cardiovascular, chemical, dermatologic, endocrine, environmental, gastroenterologic, genetic, hematologic, gynecologic, iatrogenic, infectious, musculoskeletal, neurologic, nutritional, obstetric, oncologic, otolaryngologic, pharmacologic, psychiatric, pulmonary, renal, rheumatologic, toxic, traumatic, or urologic causes; medical conditions can be causes as well.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.MedicalCause.Type
member.summary: Gets the name of the type as specified by schema.org.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.MedicalCause.CauseOf
member.summary: The condition, complication, symptom, sign, etc. caused.

member.name: T:Schema.NET.MedicalClinic
member.summary: A facility, often associated with a hospital or medical school, that is devoted to the specific diagnosis and/or healthcare. Previously limited to outpatients but with evolution it may be open to inpatients as well.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.MedicalClinic.Type
member.summary: Gets the name of the type as specified by schema.org.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.MedicalClinic.AvailableService
member.summary: A medical service available from this provider.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.MedicalClinic.MedicalSpecialty
member.summary: A medical specialty of the provider.

member.name: T:Schema.NET.MedicalCondition
member.summary: Any condition of the human body that affects the normal functioning of a person, whether physically or mentally. Includes diseases, injuries, disabilities, disorders, syndromes, etc.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.MedicalCondition.Type
member.summary: Gets the name of the type as specified by schema.org.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.MedicalCondition.AssociatedAnatomy
member.summary: The anatomy of the underlying organ system or structures associated with this entity.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.MedicalCondition.Cause
member.summary: Specifying a cause of something in general. e.g in medicine , one of the causative agent(s) that are most directly responsible for the pathophysiologic process that eventually results in the occurrence.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.MedicalCondition.DifferentialDiagnosis
member.summary: One of a set of differential diagnoses for the condition. Specifically, a closely-related or competing diagnosis typically considered later in the cognitive process whereby this medical condition is distinguished from others most likely responsible for a similar collection of signs and symptoms to reach the most parsimonious diagnosis or diagnoses in a patient.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.MedicalCondition.Drug
member.summary: Specifying a drug or medicine used in a medication procedure

member.name: P:Schema.NET.MedicalCondition.Epidemiology
member.summary: The characteristics of associated patients, such as age, gender, race etc.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.MedicalCondition.ExpectedPrognosis
member.summary: The likely outcome in either the short term or long term of the medical condition.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.MedicalCondition.NaturalProgression
member.summary: The expected progression of the condition if it is not treated and allowed to progress naturally.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.MedicalCondition.Pathophysiology
member.summary: Changes in the normal mechanical, physical, and biochemical functions that are associated with this activity or condition.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.MedicalCondition.PossibleComplication
member.summary: A possible unexpected and unfavorable evolution of a medical condition. Complications may include worsening of the signs or symptoms of the disease, extension of the condition to other organ systems, etc.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.MedicalCondition.PossibleTreatment
member.summary: A possible treatment to address this condition, sign or symptom.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.MedicalCondition.PrimaryPrevention
member.summary: A preventative therapy used to prevent an initial occurrence of the medical condition, such as vaccination.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.MedicalCondition.RiskFactor
member.summary: A modifiable or non-modifiable factor that increases the risk of a patient contracting this condition, e.g. age, coexisting condition.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.MedicalCondition.SecondaryPrevention
member.summary: A preventative therapy used to prevent reoccurrence of the medical condition after an initial episode of the condition.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.MedicalCondition.SignOrSymptom
member.summary: A sign or symptom of this condition. Signs are objective or physically observable manifestations of the medical condition while symptoms are the subjective experience of the medical condition.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.MedicalCondition.Stage
member.summary: The stage of the condition, if applicable.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.MedicalCondition.Status
member.summary: The status of the study (enumerated).

member.name: P:Schema.NET.MedicalCondition.Subtype
member.summary: A more specific type of the condition, where applicable, for example 'Type 1 Diabetes', 'Type 2 Diabetes', or 'Gestational Diabetes' for Diabetes.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.MedicalCondition.TypicalTest
member.summary: A medical test typically performed given this condition.

member.name: T:Schema.NET.MedicalConditionStage
member.summary: A stage of a medical condition, such as 'Stage IIIa'.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.MedicalConditionStage.Type
member.summary: Gets the name of the type as specified by schema.org.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.MedicalConditionStage.StageAsNumber
member.summary: The stage represented as a number, e.g. 3.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.MedicalConditionStage.SubStageSuffix
member.summary: The substage, e.g. 'a' for Stage IIIa.

member.name: T:Schema.NET.MedicalContraindication
member.summary: A condition or factor that serves as a reason to withhold a certain medical therapy. Contraindications can be absolute (there are no reasonable circumstances for undertaking a course of action) or relative (the patient is at higher risk of complications, but that these risks may be outweighed by other considerations or mitigated by other measures).

member.name: P:Schema.NET.MedicalContraindication.Type
member.summary: Gets the name of the type as specified by schema.org.

member.name: T:Schema.NET.MedicalDevice
member.summary: Any object used in a medical capacity, such as to diagnose or treat a patient.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.MedicalDevice.Type
member.summary: Gets the name of the type as specified by schema.org.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.MedicalDevice.AdverseOutcome
member.summary: A possible complication and/or side effect of this therapy. If it is known that an adverse outcome is serious (resulting in death, disability, or permanent damage; requiring hospitalization; or is otherwise life-threatening or requires immediate medical attention), tag it as a seriouseAdverseOutcome instead.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.MedicalDevice.Contraindication
member.summary: A contraindication for this therapy.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.MedicalDevice.Indication
member.summary: A factor that indicates use of this therapy for treatment and/or prevention of a condition, symptom, etc. For therapies such as drugs, indications can include both officially-approved indications as well as off-label uses. These can be distinguished by using the ApprovedIndication subtype of MedicalIndication.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.MedicalDevice.PostOp
member.summary: A description of the postoperative procedures, care, and/or followups for this device.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.MedicalDevice.PreOp
member.summary: A description of the workup, testing, and other preparations required before implanting this device.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.MedicalDevice.Procedure
member.summary: A description of the procedure involved in setting up, using, and/or installing the device.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.MedicalDevice.Purpose
member.summary: A goal towards an action is taken. Can be concrete or abstract.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.MedicalDevice.SeriousAdverseOutcome
member.summary: A possible serious complication and/or serious side effect of this therapy. Serious adverse outcomes include those that are life-threatening; result in death, disability, or permanent damage; require hospitalization or prolong existing hospitalization; cause congenital anomalies or birth defects; or jeopardize the patient and may require medical or surgical intervention to prevent one of the outcomes in this definition.

member.name: T:Schema.NET.MedicalEntity
member.summary: The most generic type of entity related to health and the practice of medicine.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.MedicalEntity.Type
member.summary: Gets the name of the type as specified by schema.org.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.MedicalEntity.Guideline
member.summary: A medical guideline related to this entity.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.MedicalEntity.LegalStatus
member.summary: The drug or supplement's legal status, including any controlled substance schedules that apply.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.MedicalEntity.MedicineSystem
member.summary: The system of medicine that includes this MedicalEntity, for example 'evidence-based', 'homeopathic', 'chiropractic', etc.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.MedicalEntity.RecognizingAuthority
member.summary: If applicable, the organization that officially recognizes this entity as part of its endorsed system of medicine.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.MedicalEntity.RelevantSpecialty
member.summary: If applicable, a medical specialty in which this entity is relevant.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.MedicalEntity.Study
member.summary: A medical study or trial related to this entity.

member.name: T:Schema.NET.MedicalGuideline
member.summary: Any recommendation made by a standard society (e.g. ACC/AHA) or consensus statement that denotes how to diagnose and treat a particular condition. Note: this type should be used to tag the actual guideline recommendation; if the guideline recommendation occurs in a larger scholarly article, use MedicalScholarlyArticle to tag the overall article, not this type. Note also: the organization making the recommendation should be captured in the recognizingAuthority base property of MedicalEntity.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.MedicalGuideline.Type
member.summary: Gets the name of the type as specified by schema.org.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.MedicalGuideline.EvidenceLevel
member.summary: Strength of evidence of the data used to formulate the guideline (enumerated).

member.name: P:Schema.NET.MedicalGuideline.EvidenceOrigin
member.summary: Source of the data used to formulate the guidance, e.g. RCT, consensus opinion, etc.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.MedicalGuideline.GuidelineDate
member.summary: Date on which this guideline's recommendation was made.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.MedicalGuideline.GuidelineSubject
member.summary: The medical conditions, treatments, etc. that are the subject of the guideline.

member.name: T:Schema.NET.MedicalGuidelineContraindication
member.summary: A guideline contraindication that designates a process as harmful and where quality of the data supporting the contraindication is sound.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.MedicalGuidelineContraindication.Type
member.summary: Gets the name of the type as specified by schema.org.

member.name: T:Schema.NET.MedicalGuidelineRecommendation
member.summary: A guideline recommendation that is regarded as efficacious and where quality of the data supporting the recommendation is sound.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.MedicalGuidelineRecommendation.Type
member.summary: Gets the name of the type as specified by schema.org.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.MedicalGuidelineRecommendation.RecommendationStrength
member.summary: Strength of the guideline's recommendation (e.g. 'class I').

member.name: T:Schema.NET.MedicalIndication
member.summary: A condition or factor that indicates use of a medical therapy, including signs, symptoms, risk factors, anatomical states, etc.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.MedicalIndication.Type
member.summary: Gets the name of the type as specified by schema.org.

member.name: T:Schema.NET.MedicalIntangible
member.summary: A utility class that serves as the umbrella for a number of 'intangible' things in the medical space.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.MedicalIntangible.Type
member.summary: Gets the name of the type as specified by schema.org.

member.name: T:Schema.NET.MedicalObservationalStudy
member.summary: An observational study is a type of medical study that attempts to infer the possible effect of a treatment through observation of a cohort of subjects over a period of time. In an observational study, the assignment of subjects into treatment groups versus control groups is outside the control of the investigator. This is in contrast with controlled studies, such as the randomized controlled trials represented by MedicalTrial, where each subject is randomly assigned to a treatment group or a control group before the start of the treatment.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.MedicalObservationalStudy.Type
member.summary: Gets the name of the type as specified by schema.org.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.MedicalObservationalStudy.StudyDesign
member.summary: Specifics about the observational study design (enumerated).

member.name: T:Schema.NET.MedicalProcedure
member.summary: A process of care used in either a diagnostic, therapeutic, preventive or palliative capacity that relies on invasive (surgical), non-invasive, or other techniques.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.MedicalProcedure.Type
member.summary: Gets the name of the type as specified by schema.org.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.MedicalProcedure.BodyLocation
member.summary: Location in the body of the anatomical structure.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.MedicalProcedure.Followup
member.summary: Typical or recommended followup care after the procedure is performed.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.MedicalProcedure.HowPerformed
member.summary: How the procedure is performed.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.MedicalProcedure.Indication
member.summary: A factor that indicates use of this therapy for treatment and/or prevention of a condition, symptom, etc. For therapies such as drugs, indications can include both officially-approved indications as well as off-label uses. These can be distinguished by using the ApprovedIndication subtype of MedicalIndication.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.MedicalProcedure.Outcome
member.summary: Expected or actual outcomes of the study.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.MedicalProcedure.Preparation
member.summary: Typical preparation that a patient must undergo before having the procedure performed.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.MedicalProcedure.ProcedureType
member.summary: The type of procedure, for example Surgical, Noninvasive, or Percutaneous.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.MedicalProcedure.Status
member.summary: The status of the study (enumerated).

member.name: T:Schema.NET.MedicalRiskCalculator
member.summary: A complex mathematical calculation requiring an online calculator, used to assess prognosis. Note: use the url property of Thing to record any URLs for online calculators.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.MedicalRiskCalculator.Type
member.summary: Gets the name of the type as specified by schema.org.

member.name: T:Schema.NET.MedicalRiskEstimator
member.summary: Any rule set or interactive tool for estimating the risk of developing a complication or condition.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.MedicalRiskEstimator.Type
member.summary: Gets the name of the type as specified by schema.org.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.MedicalRiskEstimator.EstimatesRiskOf

member.name: P:Schema.NET.MedicalRiskEstimator.IncludedRiskFactor

member.name: T:Schema.NET.MedicalRiskFactor

member.name: P:Schema.NET.MedicalRiskFactor.Type

member.name: P:Schema.NET.MedicalRiskFactor.IncreasesRiskOf

member.name: T:Schema.NET.MedicalRiskScore

member.name: P:Schema.NET.MedicalRiskScore.Algorithm

member.name: T:Schema.NET.MedicalScholarlyArticle

member.summary: A medical study is an umbrella type covering all kinds of research studies relating to human medicine or health, including observational studies and interventional trials and registries, randomized, controlled or not. When the specific type of study is known, use one of the extensions of this type, such as MedicalTrial or MedicalObservationalStudy. Also, note that this type should be used to mark up data that describes the study itself; to tag an article that publishes the results of a study, use MedicalScholarlyArticle. Note: use the code property of MedicalEntity to store study IDs, e.g. clinicaltrials.gov ID.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.MedicalStudy.Type

member.name: P:Schema.NET.MedicalStudy.HealthCondition

member.name: T:Schema.NET.SuperficialAnatomy
member.summary: Anatomical features that can be observed by sight (without dissection), including the form and proportions of the human body as well as surface landmarks that correspond to deeper subcutaneous structures. Superficial anatomy plays an important role in sports medicine, phlebotomy, and other medical specialties as underlying anatomical structures can be identified through surface palpation. For example, during back surgery, superficial anatomy can be used to palpate and count vertebrae to find the site of incision. Or in phlebotomy, superficial anatomy can be used to locate an underlying vein; for example, the median cubital vein can be located by palpating the borders of the cubital fossa (such as the epicondyles of the humerus) and then looking for the superficial signs of the vein, such as size, prominence, ability to refill after depression, and feel of surrounding tissue support. As another example, in a subluxation (dislocation) of the glenohumeral joint, the bony structure becomes pronounced with the deltoid muscle failing to cover the glenohumeral joint allowing the edges of the scapula to be superficially visible. Here, the superficial anatomy is the visible edges of the scapula, implying the underlying dislocation of the joint (the related anatomical structure).

member.name: P:Schema.NET.SuperficialAnatomy.Type
member.summary: Gets the name of the type as specified by schema.org.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.SuperficialAnatomy.AssociatedPathophysiology

member.name: P:Schema.NET.SuperficialAnatomy.RelatedAnatomy
member.summary: Anatomical systems or structures that relate to the superficial anatomy.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.SuperficialAnatomy.RelatedCondition
member.summary: A medical condition associated with this anatomy.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.SuperficialAnatomy.RelatedTherapy
member.summary: A medical therapy related to this anatomy.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.SuperficialAnatomy.Significance
member.summary: The significance associated with the superficial anatomy; as an example, how characteristics of the superficial anatomy can suggest underlying medical conditions or courses of treatment.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.JsonLdObject.Context
member.summary: Gets or sets the context used to define the short-hand names that are used throughout a JSON-LD document. These short-hand names are called terms and help developers to express specific identifiers in a compact manner. When two people communicate with one another, the conversation takes place in a shared environment, typically called "the context of the conversation". This shared context allows the individuals to use shortcut terms, like the first name of a mutual friend, to communicate more quickly but without losing accuracy. A context in JSON-LD works in the same way. It allows two applications to use shortcut terms to communicate with one another more efficiently, but without losing accuracy. Simply speaking, a context is used to map terms to IRIs. Terms are case sensitive and any valid string that is not a reserved JSON-LD keyword can be used as a term.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.JsonLdObject.Id
member.summary: Gets or sets the identifier used to uniquely identify things that are being described in the document with IRIs or blank node identifiers. To be able to externally reference nodes in a graph, it is important that nodes have an identifier. IRIs are a fundamental concept of Linked Data, for nodes to be truly linked, dereferencing the identifier should result in a representation of that node.This may allow an application to retrieve further information about a node. In JSON-LD, a node is identified using the @id keyword:
